sonal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Fräulein Nicholeus Riehm was born in 1437, in Leimen, Rhein-Neckar-Kreis, Baden-Württemberg, Germany. She married Nicholeus \"Nicholas\" Riehm in 1457, in Leimen, Rhein-Neckar-Kreis, Baden-Württemberg, Germany. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1437–":"1437–Surnud","1432–1490":"1432–1490","1465–1509":"1465–1509","1437–Female":"1437–Surnud","1437":"1437","1457":"1457","1465":"1465","1432":"1432","1509":"1509","1490":"1490","Leimen, Heidelberg, Baden-Württemberg, Germany":"Leimen, Rhein-Neckar-Kreis, Baden-Württemberg, Saksamaa","Leimen, Heidelberg, Baden, Germany":"Leimen, Amt Heidelberg, Baden"},"fi":{"1437–":"1437–Kuollut","1432–1490":"1432–1490","1465–1509":"1465–1509","1437–Female":"1437–Kuollut","1437":"1437","1457":"1457","1465":"1465","1432":"1432","1509":"1509","1490":"1490","Leimen, Heidelberg, Baden-Württemberg, Germany":"Leimen, Rhein-Neckar-Kreis, Baden-Württemberg, Saksa","Leimen, Heidelberg, Baden, Germany":"Leimen, Amt Heidelberg, Baden"},"fr":{"1437–":"1437–Décédée","1432–1490":"1432–1490","1465–1509":"1465–1509","1437–Female":"1437–Décédée","1437":"1437","1457":"1457","1465":"1465","1432":"1432","1509":"1509","1490":"1490","Leimen, Heidelberg, Baden-